Kathmandu. There are a number of ATMs in these cities. Everything is paid in Nepali rupees. So money should be exchanged before the start of the trek.\";i:6;s:191:\"Yes. Internet can be accessed in most places. Sometimes, there might be some technical problems. Internet in Nepal is not as fast as you are used to and at times you can just lose connection.\";i:7;s:547:\"Not really. It depends on you. If you want, ABC trekking can be done independently. You could hire a guide and a porter by yourself instead of going through an agency or not hire a guide at all. Although, not having a guide can be a little problematic during off season.\r\n\r\nIt really depends on you. Is it your first time in Nepal? How confident are you of being able to find your way around? How pressed on time are you? If you go through an agency, it will be costlier but everything will be planned. You will only have to come, trek and return.\";i:8;s:103:\"For Annapurna region, pay for guides range from $20 to $30 per day and porters take $15 to $25 per day.\";}}s:3:\"map\";a:2:{s:9:\"image_url\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"iframe\";s:0:\"\";}}'),
